<li id="cite_note-48"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Drug_addiction#cite_ref-48">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFLewis2018" class="citation journal">Lewis M (October 2018).  Longo DL (ed.). "Brain Change in Addiction as Learning, Not Disease". <i>The New England Journal of Medicine</i>. <b>379</b> (16): 1551–1560. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doi_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="Doi (identifier)">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://doi.org/10.1056%2FNEJMra1602872">10.1056/NEJMra1602872</a>. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PMID_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="PMID (identifier)">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30332573">30332573</a>. <q>Addictive activities are determined neither solely by brain changes nor solely by social conditions ... the narrowing seen in addiction takes place within the behavioral repertoire, the social surround, and the brain — all at the same time.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+England+Journal+of+Medicine&amp;rft.atitle=Brain+Change+in+Addiction+as+Learning%2C+Not+Disease&amp;rft.volume=379&amp;rft.issue=16&amp;rft.pages=1551-1560&amp;rft.date=2018-10&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1056%2FNEJMra1602872&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F30332573&amp;rft.aulast=Lewis&amp;rft.aufirst=M&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAddiction" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/></span>
